Then
he
smiled
pleasantly,
and
I
felt
that
externally
at
any
rate
I
possessed
the
qualifications
which
he
desired.
"You
have
come
in
answer
to
my
advertisement,
Dr.
Hamilton?"
he
asked.
"Yes,
sir."
"Do
you
fulfil
the
conditions
which
are
there
laid
down?"
"I
believe
that
I
do."
"You
are
a
powerful
man,
or
so
I
should
judge
from
your
appearance.
"I
think
that
I
am
fairly
strong."
"And
resolute?"
"I
believe
so."
"Have
you
ever
known
what
it
was
to
be
exposed
to
imminent
danger?"
"No,
I
don't
know
that
I
ever
have."
"But
you
think
you
would
be
prompt
and
cool
at
such
a
time?"
"I
hope
so."
"Well,
I
believe
that
you
would.
I
have
the
more
confidence
in
you
because
you
do
not
pretend
to
be
certain
as
to
what
you
would
do
in
a
position
that
was
new
to
you.
My
impression
is
that,
so
far
as
personal
qualities
go,
you
are
the
very
man
of
whom
I
am
in
search.
That
being
settled,
we
may
pass
on
to
the
next
point."
"Which
is?"
"To
talk
to
me
about
beetles."
I
looked
across
to
see
if
he
was
joking,
but,
on
the
contrary,
he
was
